ðŸ§© Step-by-Step Guide to Training a Snippet Generator
1. Define the Task
Goal: Given a query and a raw document (web page text), extract a concise snippet that answers the query.
Output format: A short, relevant passage (like Googleâ€™s featured snippets).
2. Prepare Your Dataset
Collect query-snippet pairs: Use datasets like MS MARCO, Natural Questions, or build your own from search logs and annotated documents.
Document preprocessing: Clean HTML, remove boilerplate (navigation, ads), and segment into meaningful passages (250â€“500 words) Google Cloud.
3. Embed and Index Passages
Use sentence or passage embeddings: Apply models like BERT, SBERT, or OpenAI embeddings to convert text into vectors.
Vector search setup: Store embeddings in a vector database (e.g., FAISS, Pinecone) for fast retrieval j.blaszyk.me.
4. Train a Retrieval Model
Objective: Match queries to relevant passages.
Approach: Fine-tune a dual-encoder or cross-encoder model on your query-snippet pairs.
Loss function: Contrastive loss or triplet loss to optimize semantic similarity.
5. Train a Snippet Selector
Input: Top-k retrieved passages.
Model: Use a ranking model (e.g., BERT-based classifier) to score and select the best snippet.
Optional: Add a summarization layer to compress longer passages into snippet-sized answers.
6. Evaluate the Model
Metrics: Use ROUGE, BLEU, and Exact Match to compare generated snippets against ground truth.
Human evaluation: Rate snippet relevance, readability, and informativeness.
7. Deploy and Tune
Pipeline integration: Combine retrieval and ranking into a real-time system.
Search tuning: Continuously improve with feedback loops and domain-specific data Google Cloud.
